        "title":  "Building a serverless A2A gateway for agent discovery, routing, and access control",
        "source":  "AWS Machine Learning Blog",
        "url":  "https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/machine-learning/building-a-serverless-a2a-gateway-for-agent-discovery-routing-and-access-control/",
        "date":  "2026-07-01",
        "theme":  "Orchestration",
        "summary":  "AWS published a technical guide for building a serverless agent-to-agent (A2A) gateway on AWS that provides a unified entry point for multi-agent systems with discovery, routing, and JWT-based access control. The architecture uses API Gateway, Lambda, DynamoDB, and Amazon Cognito to manage agent registration, OAuth authentication, and Server-Sent Events streaming. Deployment is handled via Terraform with pre-built example agents for testing.",
        "execSummary":  "This AWS guide addresses one of the hardest unsolved problems in enterprise AI deployment: how to govern, discover, and route requests across a growing fleet of specialized agents without creating a security and management nightmare. The A2A gateway pattern ΓÇö a single authenticated entry point in front of all agents ΓÇö is a direct parallel to the API gateway patterns enterprises already understand from microservices, which lowers the conceptual barrier to adoption. For enterprise architects and security leaders, the JWT and OAuth controls mean agent-to-agent communication can be audited and permissioned like any other internal API. Organizations building multi-agent workflows should treat this pattern as a baseline governance requirement, not an advanced optimization.",
        "vendorLean":  "AWS ΓÇö promotes AWS services as the foundation for agent orchestration.",
